> Analyzer analyzer =3D new StandardAnalyzer(); =20
> Query query =3D=20
> org.apache.lucene.queryParser.QueryParser.parse(queryString,=20
> "YesNo", analyzer);                   =20
> Hits hits =3D searcher.search(query);       =20
> System.out.println("Found "+hits.length()+" match");         =20
>         =20
> ---------------------
> where the value of queryString contains the user input which=20
> is wither a "Yes" or "No"
>=20
>=20
> Whenever I insert a "No", I would not be able to retrieve it=20
> (the output will show 0 mtaches) even though I use the same=20
> analyzer. Any other values like "Yes","n","y" would get hits.=20
>  Has anyone went through similar errors? Is this a bug or is=20
> it some limitation, where lucene can't accept string values=20
> of "No"? Or am i missing something?=20
>=20

The StandardAnalyzer uses a small list of english stop words. These are
common word, which will be ignored, e.g. "no" or "a". Checkout
org.apache.lucene.analysis.standard.StandardAnalyser for the full list.

You have to write your own analyzer. This is very easy: Copy the code =
from
StandardAnalyzer to your own class and remove the StopFilter or change
the list of Stopwords. Don't forget to rebuild your index after this.
Regards,
	Wolf-Dietrich

